  "riddle": "1. Seek the page about the FirstGroup regional train operator that ran local and regional services across north‑west England until its services were absorbed into another First‑branded company in the early 2000s and report how many stations this former operator called at during its service.\n\n2. There exists a simple reduction you must perform: take the station-count you just uncovered and repeatedly add its digits until only one digit remains — what is that final digit?\n\n3. How many categories of passenger operators are enumerated on the conceptual page that explains the kinds of companies running trains after privatisation?\n\n4. If you follow the link to the history of rail privatisation in Britain, you will reach an article about asset sales; to how many companies were the track maintenance and renewal assets sold according to that account?\n\n5. The article describing the cross‑Pennine operator under the 'First' brand conceals its roster size — how many fleet units did that operator run?\n\n6. In a short railway chronicle, a certain multiple‑unit is described as 247 metres long; convert that length into yards (round down to an integer) and record the result.\n\n7. The railway station that serves the main Manchester airport wears its platform count plainly on its page — how many platforms are listed there?\n\n8. (As a quick flourish) add the digits of the platform count you just noted and give me that digit-sum.\n\n9. Locate the port town on Anglesey opposite Ireland and record how many metres above sea level its principal station sits.\n\n10. Pinpoint the article for the large Cheshire junction famed for its locomotive works and state how many platforms that station has.\n\n11. Before moving on, take the platform total you just found for that junction, express it in binary, and count how many 1‑bits appear — what number do you get?\n\n12. Picture the road route between the mill town northeast of Manchester and the area serving the airport; what is the driving distance between those two places?\n\n13. The northern gateway's station page displays geographic coordinates in its summary box; capture those coordinates as given.\n\n14. Imagine driving from the Staffordshire city of pottery fame to the airport area: how many minutes would that journey take by road?\n\n15. Now take that driving-duration number and list its distinct prime factors, then add those distinct primes together — what total do they make?\n\n16. Find the market town in County Durham and note how many metres above sea level it lies.\n\n17. Compute (clue 2 + clue 7) % 10 and give the single digit (0–9) that this expression produces.",
